/*

WHAT IS ZK?
ZK is a programming language made for learning purposes.
It has the intent to be a C with modern features and *functional paradigm*

We have ZTD which is the ztandard ZK library.

We have zewages, and those are imported in function level with "+" keyword.
The zewages are just like modules that contains related impure functions, such as IO for input/output, FS for file system access, etc
and they just will be accessible by explicitly importing them in the function signature.

pure functions don't need to be inside a zewage

We have also the ":" operator from ZTD (called as "chain") that puts the left expression as the first argument of the right function.
This improves a lot the readability, for example, instead of this:
IOputs(join(reverse_arr(split_lines(unwrap(FSread("file.txt")))), "\n"));
We could have this:
FSread("file.txt") : unwrap : split_lines : reverse_arr : join("\n") : IOputs;

We also have interfaces, which *modules* can implement.

We have struct just as C;

We have string as a native type;

I think thats all;
*/

void main +IO +Conf {
  IOputs("Ol√° Mundo!");

  let c = Conf {"example", "just an example", "my/path.txt"};
  change_conf(&c);
  &c:conf_to_string:IOputs;
}
